# Cursor Rules for DevCharms Astro Blog

## Project Overview
This is an Astro-based blog and portfolio website using the AstroPaper theme with Tailwind CSS styling.

## Code Style and Standards

### General Principles
- Write concise, technical responses with accurate Astro examples
- Leverage Astro's partial hydration and multi-framework support effectively
- Prioritize static generation and minimal JavaScript for optimal performance
- Use descriptive variable names and follow Astro's naming conventions
- Organize files using Astro's file-based routing system

### File Organization
- Use the recommended Astro project structure:
  - `src/components/` - Reusable UI components
  - `src/layouts/` - Page layouts and templates
  - `src/pages/` - Route pages and dynamic routes
  - `src/styles/` - Global styles and CSS
  - `src/contents/` - Markdown content files
  - `src/utils/` - Utility functions and helpers

## Astro-Specific Rules

### Component Development
- Create `.astro` files for Astro components
- Use framework-specific components (React, Vue, Svelte) when necessary
- Implement proper component composition and reusability
- Use Astro's component props for data passing
- Leverage Astro's built-in components like `<Markdown />` when appropriate

### Routing and Pages
- Utilize Astro's file-based routing system in the `src/pages/` directory
- Implement dynamic routes using `[...slug].astro` syntax
- Use `getStaticPaths()` for generating static pages with dynamic routes
- Implement proper 404 handling with a `404.astro` page

### Content Management
- Use Markdown (`.md`) files for blog posts in `src/contents/`
- Leverage Astro's built-in support for frontmatter in Markdown files
- Follow the existing content structure for blog posts

### Styling
- Use Tailwind CSS utility classes extensively
- Leverage Tailwind's responsive design utilities (`sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`, etc.)
- Utilize Tailwind's color palette and spacing scale for consistency
- Never use the `@apply` directive
- Use Astro's scoped styling with `<style>` tags when needed

## Project-Specific Rules

### Blog Post Structure
- Follow the existing format in `src/contents/` for new blog posts
- Include proper frontmatter with title, description, tags, and publish date
- Use descriptive filenames that match the post slug

### Component Usage
- Use existing components from `src/components/` when possible
- Follow the established patterns for cards, tags, and navigation
- Maintain consistency with the current design system

### Performance
- Minimize use of client-side JavaScript; leverage Astro's static generation
- Use the `client:*` directives judiciously for partial hydration:
  - `client:load` for immediately needed interactivity
  - `client:idle` for non-critical interactivity
  - `client:visible` for components that should hydrate when visible
- Implement proper lazy loading for images and other assets

### Data Handling
- Use `Astro.props` for passing data to components
- Implement `getStaticPaths()` for fetching data at build time
- Use `Astro.glob()` for working with local files efficiently
- Follow the existing utility functions in `src/utils/`

## Development Workflow

### Before Making Changes
- Check existing components and patterns in the codebase
- Follow the established file structure and naming conventions
- Ensure new features integrate with the existing blog functionality

### Code Quality
- Use TypeScript for enhanced type safety
- Implement proper error handling and logging
- Follow Astro's Style Guide for consistent code formatting
- Write self-documenting code with clear variable names

### Testing and Validation
- Test changes in the development environment
- Ensure responsive design works across different screen sizes
- Verify that blog functionality remains intact

## File Naming Conventions
- Use kebab-case for file names (e.g., `blog-post-title.md`)
- Use PascalCase for component names (e.g., `BlogCard.astro`)
- Use camelCase for utility functions and variables

## Dependencies and Integrations
- The project uses Tailwind CSS for styling
- Tina CMS integration is available for content management
- Follow the existing configuration in `astro.config.mjs` and `tailwind.config.cjs`

## Common Patterns to Follow
- Blog posts use the `PostDetails.astro` layout
- Tags are handled through the tag system in `src/pages/tags/`
- Search functionality is implemented in the `Search.tsx` component
- Social icons and navigation follow the established patterns

## When in Doubt
- Check existing implementations in the codebase
- Follow Astro's official documentation for best practices
- Maintain consistency with the current design and functionality
- Prioritize user experience and performance
